<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Warns About Safety of Foreigners </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0702183594 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1709 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0702183594 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, 7 Feb (TANJUG) -- "The Serb side has a 
legitimate right to defend itself with every available means; if 
we are attacked from the air we will not sit idly by," president 
of the Srpska republic Radovan Karadzic said at a news 
conference this evening. 
  "We now have firm control of our army and we can guarantee 
the safety of foreigners in our republic, but in the event of an 
attack elements of chaos would emerge and I am not sure that any 
foreigners in Bosnia-Herzegovina would be safe -- not because we 
would issue such orders, but because the people would treat 
foreigners as enemies, which they really would be, in a way," 
Karadzic said. 
  Speaking about the letter sent to NATO by UN Secretary 
General Butrus-Ghali, Karadzic said that such a reaction in fact 
encouraged the Muslims to reapply the same war methodology, for 
-- as he put it -- this was not the first massacre, and it was 
established that some had been committed by the Muslims 
themselves [sentence as received]. Karadzic said that the Serbs 
completely understand the emotional side of this tragedy, which 
they have condemned in the most vehement terms. 
  "We demand a rigorous investigation to identify the 
perpetrators of the crime -- once that has been done the 
international community will not have to grope in the dark. 
This is why this case should be investigated in great detail, 
not only from the ballistic, but also from the forensic aspect 
for there are some indications that this was another case of a 
stage-managed event," President Karadzic said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

