<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tesanj Muslims Issue Anti-Izetbegovic Statement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0702193294 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1854 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0702193294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Banja Luka, Feb 7 (TANJUG) -- Moslems from Tesanj, 
in the north of the former Yugoslav republic of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, publicly expressed their opposition to the 
policy of the Bosnian Moslem fundamentalist leader Alija 
Izetbegovic after a six-month silent resistance. 
  In a local radio programme monitored in the neighbouring 
Serb 
town of Banja Luka a proclamation was read accusing Izetbegovic 
of a policy of war with the creation of an Islamic state, a 
jamahiriya, in Bosnia-Herzegovina as its main objective. 
  "The policy carried out by Izetbegovic so far has brought us 
to the verge of a catastrophe ... we could have separated from 
each other and remained in peace with the Serbs and the Croats, 
but they started to stir us up, to teach us that we are of 
Moslem origin and that particularily the Serbs have been our 
century-old enemies", the proclamation reads. 
  Emphasizing that they wanted neither an autonomy nor a 
jamahiriya the Moslems from Tesanj called on their countrymen in 
Bosnia- Herzegovina to stand up against those who are for the 
continuation of bloodshed which will result in their eradication. 
  "Do not let them push us into a prolonged war against the 
Serbs", the proclamation states calling on the Islamic 
fundamentalists to leave the Tesanj area and to let the local 
Moslems continue to live in peace with or besides the Serbs and 
the Croats. 
  "We shall reach an agreement with the Serbs, let us not 
allow 
the fundamentalists to change our language and our culture", the 
Moslems from Tesanj said adding that they did not wish to 
prevent those who wanted to continue fighting for the "crazy 
ideas of a state founded on Islam". 
  The proclamation is the most direct confirmation of numerous 
indications in the last few months about the resistance of the 
local Moslems from Tesanj to Izetbegovic's policy. 
  There are also reports about agitations within the 110th 
Brigade of the Bosnian Croat Army (HVO), stationed in the Tesanj 
area, whose representatives contact units of the Bosnian Serbs 
more and more frequently with the aim of reaching a peace 
settlement. 
  These efforts have so far not yielded results because of the 
resistance of the Islamic fundamentalists dominating the Moslem 
units, loyal to Izetbegovic in the Tesanj area. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

