<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tudjman Receives Slovene Prime Minister </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0702152394 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1400 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0702152394 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In the presidential palace today Dr. Franjo Tudjman, 
president of the Republic of Croatia, received Janez Drnovsek, 
prime minister of the Republic of Slovenia, who had previously 
held talks with the Croatian Government delegation about 
relations between the two countries. Agreements on bilateral 
cooperation were also signed, the president's office has 
announced. 
  The two prime ministers, Janez Drnovsek and Nikica Valentic, 
informed President Tudjman about the agreements the two 
delegations signed during their talks. Both prime ministers 
agreed that their meeting today signified a major step in the 
further rapprochement between the two states and in building 
confidence and trade cooperation, in particular. The views of 
the two sides on a number of outstanding problems such as the 
border issue and Ljubljanska Banka [the Ljubljana Bank] 
converged even further today. These issues are expected to be 
resolved soon for the benefit of both sides. 
  At the end of the meeting President Tudjman and Prime 
Minister Drnovsek spoke about the situation in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina and the possibilites for resolving the crisis 
in the area of former Yugoslavia. 
  The Slovene prime minister was accompanied by his Foreign 
Minister Lojze Peterle and Slovene Ambassador to Croatia Matija 
Valesic. In addition to Prime Minister Valentic, on the 
Croatian side the talks were attended by Jure Radic, head of 
President Tudjman's office; Deputy Prime Minister and Minister 
of Foreign Affairs Mate Granic; Croatian Ambassador to Slovenia 
Miljenko Zagar; President Tudjman's foreign policy adviser 
Zeljko Matic, and his aide-de-camp Brigadier Kresimir Kaspar. 

</TEXT>

