<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meciar on Coalition Talks, Opposition Moves </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0702183994 Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1400 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0702183994 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1400 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] During coalition talks in Bratislava today, Vladimir 
Meciar, the prime minister and chairman of the Movement for a 
Democratic Slovakia, called on Ludovit Cernak, the chairman of 
the Slovak National Party [SNS], to resign from the post of 
deputy chairman of the National Council. He justified this by 
saying that Mr. Cernak had refused to give guarantees that he 
would coordinate the parliament's session on 16 February in a 
way that would ensure a joint action by all coalition members. 
  Speaking at a news briefing, the prime minister went on to 
say that representatives of the opposition held talks on methods 
of turning the discussion on the big privatization bill into an 
immediate political solution and noted that they would express a 
lack of confidence in Parliament Chairman Ivan Gasparovic. This 
failed to happen only because the Party of the Democratic Left 
rejected it, Vladimir Meciar added. 
  SNS Honorable Chairman Jozef Prokes confirmed the prime 
minister's statement that they proposed an open coalition 
[otvorena koalicia] to the Party of the Democratic Left [PDL]. 
He said the response of PDL representatives was slightly 
negative but not altogether dismissive. 

</TEXT>

