<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Owen Discusses Meeting With Milosevic </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0702164994 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1619 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0702164994 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, Feb 7 (TANJUG) -- Co-chairman of the 
international conference on the former Yugoslavia David Owen 
said here Monday that nobody wanted air strikes on artillery 
positions around Sarajevo, the capital of the war-shattered 
former Yugoslav republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  Only someone who is crazy could want these air strikes, Owen 
said adding however that the present situation in which so many 
people were being killed, like in Sarajevo on Saturday, could no 
longer be tolerated. He made this statement after his meeting 
with Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic Monday. 
  The mortar shell, fired Saturday from positions still 
undetermined by UNPROFOR, killed 68 and injured almost 200 
persons. 
  Owen described as extremely important his meeting with 
Milosevic which was also attended by the second co-chairman on 
the conference of the former Yugoslavia Thorvald Stoltenberg and 
Yugoslav Foreign Minister Vladislav Jovanovic. 
  One of the main topics discussed was the war in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina and ways of ending it, as well as ways of 
preventing tragedies like the one that happened in Sarajevo on 
Saturday, Lord Owen said. 
  In answer to questions about air strikes Owen said he 
favoured negotiations and expressed hope that through 
negotiations steps would be adopted to prevent tragedies like 
the one in Sarajevo. 
  Concerning his talks Sunday evening with the president of 
the 
Bosnian Serb Republic Radovan Karadzic Owen said that Karadzic 
accepted the proposal to negotiate about the demilitarization of 
Sarajevo and its placement under a two-year UN administration. 
  Lord Owen announced that the talks on Sarajevo set for 
Thursday would discuss confidence-building measures and not the 
global peace settlement for the Bosnian crisis. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-30766 </DOCNO>
