<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Inter-European Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ducky on Imports Protection </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0402170494 Prague CTK in English 1050 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0402170494 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague Feb 4 (CTK) -- If the Slovak market is to be 
protected from imports, the reason concerns the balance 
payments, Economics Minister Jan Ducky told CTK today. 
  He was referring to the statement made by Slovak Premier 
Vladimir Meciar at the Wednesday [2 February] meeting of the 
Movement for a Democratic Slovakia (HZDS), of which he is 
chairman, announcing protective measures against imports even 
from the Czech Republic. 
  Ducky said the intention was to protect the Slovak currency. 
The instability of the Slovak crown could cause problems with 
the exchange of goods. He stressed there was no contradiction 
between Meciar's statement and his own participation in talks on 
trade liberalisation. 
  The individual partners of the Central European Free Trade 
Agreement (CEFTA) do not agree on the timing of steps towards 
liberalisation. While Slovakia and the Czech Republic are 
progressing towards it, Poland and Hungary are moving "more 
slowly," he said. 
  Ducky said the idea of expanding CEFTA, possibly by the 
inclusion of Slovenia, Bulgaria and Romania, was good because, 
given the competition, the free trade zone needed about 200 
million people. The present CEFTA countries have a total 
population of 65 million. 
  The reason why mutual trade within CEFTA was developing only 
slowly was the fact that the member states were first of all 
attempting to try out independent policies, he explained. What 
is more, since their economies were all bogged down with heavy 
industry, the countries experienced the same shortages and 
surpluses. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

