<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Baudys, Slovakia Official Outline Army Size </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0302202394 Prague CTK in English 1903 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0302202394 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vranov nad Dyji, South Moravia Feb 3 (CTK) -- The 
final number of troops in the Slovak Army will be decreased from 
the current 42,000 to 35,000, Slovak Defence Minister Imrich 
Andrejcak said today after meeting with his Czech counterpart, 
Antonin Baudys. 
  Baudys confirmed that by the end of 1995 the Czech Army 
would 
reach its final size -- 65,000 troops. He said, however, that 
further decrease in the army size was not being considered thus 
far because, Baudys said, following the euphoria after the fall 
of the Berlin Wall and the collapse of the Soviet bloc, "a more 
realistic standpoint is gaining the upper hand and the 
restriction of armed forces in individual countries is coming to 
a halt." He added that the share of military expenditures in 
the state budgets of a number of European countries has begun to 
grow again. 

</TEXT>

