<F P=100> BULGARIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Opposes `Armed Involvement' in B-H </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0702142494 Sofia Khorizont Radio Network in Bulgarian 1400 
GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0702142494 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia Khorizont Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Bulgarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] At a meeting on 7 February President Zhelyu Zhelev, 
Prime Minister Lyuben Berov, and Foreign Minister Stanislav 
Daskalov discussed current issues of Bulgarian foreign policy. 
Presidential Spokesman Valentin Stoyanov supplies further 
details: 
  [Begin Stoyanov recording] Basic attention was devoted to 
the visit of Lord Owen and Stoltenberg to Bulgaria and the 
forthcoming Geneva meeting of the foreign ministers of countries 
bordering on former Yugoslavia. Bulgaria's position is as 
follows: It will participate in the meeting only if the foreign 
ministers of all invited countries participate. The president 
expressed his doubt whether this meeting could contribute 
anything to achieving peace in Bosnia-Herzegovina, especially 
against the background of Saturday's [5 February] massacre in 
Sarajevo. 
  It was again pointed out that Bulgaria's position on the 
situation in former Yugoslavia remains unchanged. Bulgaria 
opposes any armed involvement in the conflict of Balkan or other 
countries bordering on former Yugoslavia. In the past other 
countries joined this position, and recently Greece repeated 
that it adheres to the same position. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

