<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Joint Border Commission With Albania Proposed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0402140694 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1321 GMT 4 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0402140694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 4 Feb (TANJUG)--Following the latest 
incidents on the border between Yugoslavia and Albania, the 
Federal Ministry of Foreign Affairs has issued the following 
statement: 
  "As the Yugoslav public is aware, the number of incidents on 
the Yugoslav-Albanian border, in which several Albanian citizens 
regrettably lost their lives while attempting to illegally cross 
into Yugoslavia, has recently increased. 
  "In order to discuss additional measures that could be 
taken, 
in the spirit of respect for the international and bilateral 
obligations that both countries have undertaken to prevent 
border incidents, the Yugoslav side has recently proposed to the 
relevant Albanian bodies that an extraordinary session of the 
main joint Yugoslav-Albanian commission for border incidents be 
held in Belgrade." 
  The statement goes on to say: "The normalization of 
relations 
on the Yugoslav-Albanian border would improve relations between 
the two countries, which the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, 
adhering to the principles of good-neighborliness, has as its 
lasting goal." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

