<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Agrees To Croatian Office in Belgrade </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0802150594 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1403 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0802150594 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, Feb 8 (TANJUG) -- The Government of the 
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia on Tuesday gave its agreement for 
the opening of an office of the Republic of Croatia in Belgrade. 
  On the basis of a joint decleration, jointly signed by the 
representatives of Yugoslavia and Croatia in Geneva on January 
19, a Yugoslav bureau will also be opened in Zagreb. 
  The bureaus should secure communication between the two 
governments, ease the resolution of open issues, build up mutual 
trust and establish the normalization of good-neighbourly 
relations, cooperation and stability in the region, the Yugoslav 
government said. 
  The Yugoslav Government also adopted a platform for talks 
between the Yugoslav and Croatian vice-premiers -- Zeljko Simic 
and Mate Granic -- in Zagreb on February 12 and empowered Simic 
to sign a document on the status of the bureaus which will 
employ eight people each. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

