<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   PSL-SLD Talks End </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0802225094 Warsaw Third Program Radio Network in Polish 
2200 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0802225094 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw Third Program Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] We go over to Monika Olejnik, who is at the 
government hotel on Parkowa Street: 
  [Olejnik] The talks between the Polish Peasant Party [PSL] 
and the Democratic Left Alliance [SLD] have just ended, and a 
communique was read to us. It states that Poland needs economic 
development, an improvement in people's living standards, 
political stabilization, and a credible position in the world. 
The SLD and the PSL confirm this aim and express conviction as 
to the need for joint actions for its implementation. The PSL 
and the SLD adopt the principle of solid support for the draft 
budget presented by the government. 
  After discussing the resignation of Deputy Premier Marek 
Borowski and the circumstances accompanying it, the 
representatives of the SLD and the PSL express recognition of 
his knowledge, competence, and activism; they confirm that the 
SLD will present a candidature for the vacant post, in 
accordance with the coalition agreement, that together with its 
appendixes remains fully applicable. 
  The PSL and SLD leaders told journalists after the meeting 
that the coalition between the PSL and the SLD still exists. 
Marek Borowski told us that he knows the candidacy of the 
person who should take over the post of deputy prime minister 
and minister of finance in his place, but he will not reveal his 
name to us. 

</TEXT>

