<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Budget Deficit Reaches Sk4.5 Billion in Jan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0802171794 Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1100 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0802171794 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1100 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Slovak state budget deficit reached 4.5 billion 
Slovak korunas [Sk] in January 1994 and was caused by assistance 
given to the National Insurance Fund. This is what Julius Toth, 
minister of finance and deputy prime minister, told journalists 
during a break in the government's meeting today. According to 
Toth, Slovakia's imports from the Czech Republic are clearly 
specified, and Slovakia is linked to our western neighbor 
through several commercial agreements and operations that cannot 
be abandoned merely because Slovakia is faced with temporary 
problems. 
  Toth ruled out [the introduction of] the import surcharge. 
However, he went on to say that the introduction of special 
checks on the borders [between the Czech Republic and Slovakia], 
as reported by TA SR [Slovak news agency], is being considered. 
In the first phase, these checks should concern only 
foodstuffs. In the second phase, they should cover all goods en 
bloc. 

</TEXT>

