<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Interviewed on Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0802204794 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1700 
GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0802204794 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Czech Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus by Lucie </F>
Weissova at the conclusion of his visit to Israel; place and 
date not given--recorded] 
  [Excerpts] [Weissova] Mr. Prime Minister, the official 
talks with Israeli senior figures are now behind you, so I would 
like to ask you what the aims of your trip to Israel were and 
whether your talks fulfilled your expectations. 
  [Klaus] This is the first visit by a prime minister of our 
country to Israel. I think our relations with Israel have 
always been good. The episode when we had a communist regime 
should be quickly erased. This was the main aim of our 
visit--to learn about the situation in this complicated region. 
It is really not enough to read books and articles about it; 
you need to see it yourself. [passage omitted] The other aim 
was to tell people here about our country. [passage omitted] 
  The last thing is something more specific. For a long time, 
we found ourselves deadlocked as regards an agreement on the 
protection of investments; we signed agreements with a number of 
countries without any problems. However, there was a great 
problem here because of our different views on the repatriation 
of investment profits. Our negotiators had been unable to reach 
a consensus, and the matter really called for a decision to be 
made by two prime ministers--and we took it. We signed a joint 
communique, and the agreement can be signed soon. 
  And something even more important: We are interested in 
opposing protectionism anywhere in the world and are therefore 
offering free trade zones. [passage omitted] 
  I think we have managed to reach the joint conclusion with 
the Israeli side that Israel, too, is interested in creating 
such a zone between our country and Israel soon. This is also 
included in the joint communique that Prime Minister Rabin and I 
signed. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

