<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mazowiecki Supports `All Means' for Sarajevo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0702223194 Warsaw PAP in English 2123 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0702223194 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, Feb. 7 -- Former prime minister, and leader 
of the Democratic Union (UD) Tadeusz Mazowiecki called on Monday 
for "all means necessary, including military force" to be used 
to end the siege of Sarajevo. 
  Mazowiecki is the special raporteur on Yugoslavia for the 
U.N. Commission on Human Rights. He made his remarks at a 
commission meeting at Geneva following the massacre of civilians 
in Sarajevo on Saturday when a mortar bomb killed 68 people and 
wounded 200. 
  Mazowiecki said that Saturday's crime was not only an 
accusation against its perpetrators, but also against those who 
remained inactive or "again restricted themselves to words." 
  Mazowiecki pointed out that in August 1992 in his first 
report he had recommended that heavy arms which were being used 
by the Serbs to bomb Sarajevo be seized. He also recalled the 
U.N. Security Council resolution of May 6, 1993 under which 
Sarajevo and 5 other towns were placed in a "security zone." 
  He called for the Human Rights Commission to demand that the 
U.N. secretary-general and the Security Council take action to 
"bring into force their resolutions guaranteeing safety to the 
civilian population." Mazowiecki thought that the perpetrators 
of Saturday's crime should stand before a tribunal to be set up 
by the U.N. 
  On February 24 Mazowiecki is to publish another report on 
atrocities perpetrated in the former Yugoslavia. He then 
intends to resign as special raporteur. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

