<H3> <TI>   Daily Cites UN Inspectors on Embargo Busting </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0802134894 Sofia BTA in English 1155 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0802134894 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From BTA press review] </F>
  [Text] Sofia, February 8 (BTA) -- "Yugo-Embargo Repeatedly 
Violated," reads the headline of a front-paged report in the 
DEMOKRATSIYA daily of the Union of Democratic Forces (SDS). 
"Mr. Berov's cabinet is about to finally ruin your country's 
reputation by its inadequate policy and the continual 
Yugo-embargo busting," representatives of UN Sanctions 
Assistance Mission told DEMOKRATSIYA in an informal talk. 
Reportedly, they were categorical that evidence of sanctions 
busting could be found at all state administration levels. "The 
silence and inaction of the government implies blending of 
organized economic crime and government officials," the daily 
writes. According to the paper, at least four trains crossed 
the border with Serbia at Kalotina-Dragoman on Saturday and 
Sunday (February 5-6), one of them carrying 53 tanks of aviation 
petrol. 
  Answering some accusations in an interview for OTECHESTVEN 
VESTNIK, the chief of the Central Service for Organized Crime 
Control, Col. Fedor Vladimirov, points out that "nobody has 
tried to misuse the information the Organized Crime Control 
Service has in its possession." Saying that the service he 
heads has "ample" information about attempted embargo busting 
and that investigative proceedings have also been initiated, 
Col. Vladimirov refuses to give further details because the 
information is top secret. 

</TEXT>

