<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nekvasil Warns of `New Dimension' in B-H War </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0802175894 Prague CTK in English 1659 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0802175894 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Feb 8 (CTK) -- Army Chief of Staff Major 
General Jiri Nekvasil said today that aerial bombardments in 
Bosnia would give the war in the former Yugoslavia a new 
dimension. 
  The high state of NATO weaponry would allow very precise and 
selective bombardment, he said: "From a technical point of 
view, it's no problem." Much more complicated is to evaluate 
the results of such a strike and what sense it would make, what 
it would solve and what would happen afterward. This is the 
reason it is being weighed by so many parties. 
  It is also necessary to consider what could happen to 
UNPROFOR [UN Protection Forces] forces already on the ground in 
Bosnia. "The number of warring parties could go up to four," he 
said, adding UNPROFOR to the Croats, Serbs, and Muslims already 
at war. "The UN Peacekeeping Forces are not armed enough to 
stand up to everything which could follow a probable aerial 
attack," he concluded. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-30851 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu027__a94012" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-027-A </AU>
