<F P=101> Hungary </F>
<H3> <TI>   Assembly Ratifies Minority Accord With Slovenia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0802194694 Budapest MTI in English 1852 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0802194694 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 8 February (MTI) -- Hungary's parliament 
on Tuesday [8 February] unanimously ratified an agreement giving 
reciprocal rights to ethnic Slovenians in Hungary and Hungarians 
in Slovenia. State Secretary Andras Kelemen said the November 
1992 accord could set an example for similar deals with other 
countries. 
  Kelemen said ethnic Hungarians and Italians in Slovenia can 
use their native language in education and administration, and 
take part in law-making by means of positive discrimination. 
The Slovenian Constitution allows native minorities to use 
their mother tongue in official contacts at their places of 
residence. 
  Under today's agreement, national minorities can freely keep 
in touch with the parent country, study in their native tongue 
at all levels of education, found learning groups, set up 
native-language information networks, and make business links 
abroad. Hungary has more than 5,000 ethnic Slovenian citizens. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

