<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Poland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia's Yerin Visits, Discusses Cooperation </TI></H3>
<H4>   `Coordinated' Anticrime Action </H4>
<F P=102> LD0702201294 Warsaw PAP in English 1941 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0702201294 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, Feb. 7 -- Polish Interior Minister Andrzej 
Milczanowski and his Russian counterpart Victor Yerin on Monday 
announced coordinated measures against organized crime. At a 
press conference that concluded Yerin's three-day visit to 
Poland, Milczanowski added that the Polish police is considering 
the purchase of Russian arms. 
  Both ministers said they want to intensify cooperation in 
combatting organized crime, especially drug smuggling. The 
scope of such cooperation is determined by the inter-ministerial 
agreement signed in November 1992, which was reviewed during 
Yerin's present visit. 
  Reporting on the possibility to carry out joint actions 
against organized crime, Milczanowski disclosed that during the 
coming month, the Russian Interior Ministry will make a 
catalogue of crimes associated with Russian citizens in Poland 
which will be made available to Polish policemen. A similar 
catalogue will be made by Polish police to help Russian law 
enforcement. 
  Russians were second (after Ukrainians) among foreigners 
suspected of committing crimes in Poland last year when their 
number reached 667. 
  Victor Yerin said that both countries are ready to exchange 
liaison officers but that the decisions must be made by both 
governments. Asked whether foreigners are safe in Russia he 
replied that "their security is guaranteed if they behave 
normally." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

