<H3> <TI>   National Democrats Join Right-Wing Coalition </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0802202894 Warsaw PAP in English 1937 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0802202894 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, Feb. 8 -- The National Democratic Party 
(SND) led by Jan Zamoyski on Tuesday signed a policy agreement 
with the right-wing coalition formed by the Real Politics Union 
(UPR), the Conservative Party (PK), the Peasant-Christian Party 
(SLCH) and the Party of Christian Democrats (PCHD). 
  Leaders of the five groupings stressed that the coalition is 
of a confederation character and that there are proper 
conditions at present to form a conservative and liberal camp, 
as time will act to the advantage of such a camp. 
  Leader of the Conservative Party Aleksander Hall said that 
the formation of such a camp will decide whether the Right in 
Poland will score a success. He stressed that his party is 
determined to form a strong right-wing centre in the coalition. 
  The SND was set up in April 1992. At present the party has 
about one thousand members. 

</TEXT>

