<H3> <TI>   Comments by Moldova's Snegur Draw Reaction </TI></H3>
<H4>   Agrarian Party Leader Reacts </H4>
<F P=102> AU0702181594 Bucharest ROMPRES in English 1713 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0702181594 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest ROMPRES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Quotation marks as received] </F>
  [Text] Bucharest ROMPRES, 7/2/1994 -- Victor Surdu, 
president of the Democratic Agrarian Party of Romania [PDAR], 
said Snegur's and Motpan's [president of the Agrarian Democratic 
Party of Moldova] recent statements were actually "a carbon copy 
of the theses through which for many tragic decades the brothers 
across the Prut were kept under imperial boot, their rights to 
real national existence violated, their history and language 
ignored, in the name of hegemonic, dictatorial claims backed 
with criminal cynicism through the Molotov-Ribbentrop Pact". 
  The Agrarian Democratic Party, its leader Victor Surdu said, 
"considers that through such statements that contradict the 
historical truths and the course of so far of the relations 
between Romania and the Republic of Moldova, whose independence 
our country was the first to recognize -- their authors oppose 
the natural course of history, commit themselves with fishy 
haste to a direction with unforeseeable ends. Their positions 
cannot be legitimated by any argument. Moreover, they advance 
dangerous ideas, disregard an independent, sovereign and unitary 
state like Romania. 
  "Through such statements, which the PDAR definitely rejects, 
their authors assume a serious responsibility before history and 
their own citizens so tragically tried by insane decisions made 
in the past. They claim rights they really do not have towards 
their destiny. And the territorial claims that result from the 
strange outlook on the union of the Republic of Moldova with a 
part of a neighbour and sovereign state disclose a grave 
departure even from the rational and realistic spirit, a 
worrying betrayal of history and of the real and essential 
interests of the Romanians across the Prut. 
  Hearing with surprise, sorrow and worry such statements, 
firmly rejecting them, the PDAR is sure that the truth will 
triumph, that future history will do justice to people so hard 
tried by fate, by foreign oppression, that the Romanians 
everywhere, just like their brave forefathers, will know how to 
defend their rights, faith, language and national being. 

</TEXT>

