<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Croatia's Granic, Bosnia's Silajdzic Hold Talks </TI></H3>
<H4>   Hostilities `Must End Immediately' </H4>
<F P=102> LD0902152094 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1400 GMT 9 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0902152094 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Tihomir Vinkovic from Geneva] </F>
  [Text] Mate Granic, Croatian deputy prime minister and 
minister of foreign affairs, and Bosnian Prime Minister Haris 
Silajdzic ended their first round of talks at about 1300. Their 
tete-a-tete meeting took place in a constructive atmosphere at 
the Richmond hotel. The two ministers came to the conclusion 
that the hostilities between Croats and Muslims in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina must end immediately. Future relations will 
be determined on the basis of an agreement. 
  The future status of Muslim and Croat people in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina appears to be controversial. Proposals have 
ranged from the organization of Bosnia-Herzegovina along 
cantonal lines to the setting up of republics within a 
Bosnia-Herzegovina federation. 
  The talks, according to reports, were the first to be held 
in 
a completely frank atmospohere and could form a basis for a 
solution. 
  Croatian Minister Granic explained the features and basic 
guidelines of the Croatian-FRY statement on the normalization of 
relations: It deals exclusively with humanitarian issues and 
those connected with communications and is in no way targeted 
against Muslims in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  The negotiating circles say that the international community 
as well as influential countries have been putting pressure on 
both sides to reach an agreement. The talks held so far appear 
to have taken this course. 
  Minister Granic will this afternoon meet the Austrian and 
Romanian foreign ministers who are attending the talks between 
Cochairmen Owen and Stoltenberg and representatives from the 
countries neighboring the former Yugoslavia. He is also 
expected to meet Silajdzic once again late this evening. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

