<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Croatia's Granic, Bosnia's Silajdzic Hold Talks </TI></H3>
<H4>   Granic Presents Croatian View </H4>
<F P=102> LD0902183694 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1800 GMT 9 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0902183694 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Tihomir Vinkovic from Geneva] </F>
  [Excerpt] In his talks with Bosnia-Herzegovina Prime 
Minister Haris Silajdzic and Austrian Foreign Minister Mock in 
Geneva today, Mate Granic, Croatian deputy prime minister and 
minister of foreign affairs, presented the Croatian standpoint 
on the possible future of Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  A union of republics of Bosnia-Herzegovina would consist of 
three republics in which one of the three constituent nations 
would be in the majority. Minority rights in each of the 
republics in the union would be guaranteed and supervised by the 
international community. In areas where they make up a compact 
body, the minorities could be organized in areas with a certain 
degree of autonomy. In case the union of republics of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina disintegrates, each republic would have to 
guarantee the same minority rights as is envisaged for the union. 
  The Croatian view is identical to the EU proposal, known as 
the Kinkel-Juppe plan. Croatia again reiterated its proposal 
that the international community should supervise the border 
between Croatia and Bosnia-Herzegovina, and carry out inspection 
of military formations. Of course, all hostilities must first 
cease. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

