<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Owen Optimistic on Withdrawal of Artillery </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1002130994 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1210 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1002130994 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Geneva, Feb 10 (TANJUG) -- Co-Chairman of the 
International Conference on the Former Yugoslavia, Lord Owen on 
Thursday said he believed chances were good that the agreement 
on a ceasefire and the withdrawal of artillery from positions 
around Sarajevo and its placing under the control of U.N. 
peace-keepers would be honoured. 
  Bosnian Serb and Muslim military representatives on 
Wednesday 
reached a ceasefire agreement through the mediation of U.N. 
Protection Force (UNPROFOR) Commander for the Former Yugoslav 
Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina, General Michael Rose. The 
ceasefire agreement is to go into effect at noon on Thursday. 
The two sides also agreed to place their artillery weapons 
under UNPROFOR control while the ceasefire agreement is in force. 
  Lord Owen said the NATO ultimatum for Serbs to pull back 
their artillery to lines 20 kilometers from the centre of 
Sarajevo or else air strikes against them would be launched had 
had a strong impact on the Serbs. 
  Owen said in a statement to BBC Radio he hoped that, at the 
next round of the peace talks on Bosnia-Herzegovina, opening on 
Thursday afternoon, the parties would reach agreement to appoint 
a U.N. administrator-designate for Sarajevo in preparation for 
the city's demilitarization. 

</TEXT>

