<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karadzic Walks Out of Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1002131394 Paris AFP in English 1312 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1002131394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, Feb 10 (AFP) -- Bosnian Serb leader Radovan 
Karadzic walked out of peace talks here Wednesday [as received], 
saying he refused to participate unless the responsibility for a 
mortar attack in Sarajevo that killed 68 was determined. 
  The routine meeting here came the day after NATO, reacting 
to 
Saturday's mortar attack, issued an ultimatum of February 21 for 
heavy artillery to be withdrawn from around Serb-besieged 
Sarajevo or it would launch air strikes. Karadzic had earlier 
threatened not to participate but then met with his Bosnian 
Moslem and Croat adversaries under the aegis of EC and UN 
mediators. 

</TEXT>

