<F P=100> ROMANIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   PDSR on IMF Memorandum, Snegur Statements </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0802205394 Bucharest Radio Romania Network in Romanian 
1400 GMT 8 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0802205394 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest Radio Romania Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Romanian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mr. Oliviu Gherman, president of the ruling Social 
Democracy Party of Romania [PDSR], said at his party's news 
conference today that the provisions of the IMF memorandum, 
which are a substantial part of the economic policy of our 
country, must be discussed in the parliament because the ruling 
party is interested in having this accord represent the 
political option of all parties and should not be solved through 
a simple signature on the document. 
  Regarding another issue, Mr. Gherman assessed that the open 
letter addressed to the parties that belong to the Democratic 
Convention and the Democratic Party represents the decision of 
the permanent delegation and means that the ruling party is open 
for political dialogue. In the view of the PDSR, three stages 
are necessary to finalize the dialogue: to establish the 
principles for a cooperation in the political arena; to work out 
a program regarding the unfolding of the reform in Romania; and 
to hold discussions on the basis of a government coalition. 
  Referring to the recent declarations made by the president 
of 
the Republic of Moldova and Agrarian Party leader, Ioan Solcanu, 
vice president of the PDSR, expressed his concern that such 
pro-Russian ideologies tend to become state policy. The message 
of the PDSR is the following: We should not forget that all of 
us are Romanians and history cannot be distorted according to 
momentary interests. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

