<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Adviser Denies Walesa Interference </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0902143594 Warsaw PAP in Polish 1108 GMT 9 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0902143594 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, 9 Feb -- Asked by a PAP journalist to 
comment on views that while signing Borowski's resignation, the 
president exerted influence on reaching a quick agreement within 
the coalition, Andrzej Zakrzewski, head of the office for 
political services to the president, said that Lech Walesa "does 
not interfere with the coalition, but simply learns what the 
coalition and the government are `producing.'" 
  Zakrzewski added that the president signed Borowski's 
resignation "in accordance with the procedures." 
  "According to the president, what happened is the internal 
matter of the coalition and the government; the matter of 
observing the agreements and following the procedure of changes 
in the cabinet. The president has nothing to do with it, and he 
can only accept the changes, and this is what he did," 
Zakrzewski said. 
  Asked whether he does not think that the president accepted 
Borowski's resignation unexpectedly quickly, Zakrzewski replied: 
"The president is always quick." 

</TEXT>

