<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs Threaten Retaliation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1002120194 Paris AFP in English 1157 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1002120194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pale, Bosnia-Herzegovina, Feb 10 (AFP) -- Bosnia's 
Serbs Thursday [10 February] rejected NATO's ultimatum to end 
their siege of Sarajevo and said their heavy weapons would not 
be removed from around the city. 
  "Despite this ultimatum, the Serb artillery will not move an 
inch," said their main spokesman, Miroslav Toholj. "We are ready 
to retaliate." 
  He called the NATO threat to hit Serb positions with air 
strikes if the artillery is not pulled back within 10 days as "a 
terrorist threat" and said the Serbs would respond "by all 
means" to any attack. 

</TEXT>

