<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Welcomes NATO Ultimatum </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1002090994 Paris AFP in English 0856 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1002090994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, Feb 10 (AFP) -- Bosnian Prime Minister Haris 
Silajdzic said peace may be at hand this time in Bosnia. 
  "There is a line that has been crossed," he said, the line 
being the willingness to use force as NATO issued an ultimatum 
Wednesday [9 February] for an end to shelling of Sarajevo and 
withdrawal of heavy weapons. 
  It "might be the first step towards disengagement," he said. 
  Asked by AFP at his hotel here if the peace initiative would 
really work, after so many have failed, Silajdzic said: "I 
think it will." 
  Silajdzic is in Geneva for a Bosnian peace conference 
opening 
Thursday. 
  He said the withdrawal of the artillery of the besieging 
Serbs from around Sarajevo would not change the strategic 
balance since it is "not true you can protect troops with 
artillery." He said the only purpose of the Serb artillery was 
"to attack civilians." 
  Military experts in Sarajevo consider, however, that the 
Serbs' artillery advantage enables them to offset the numerical 
superiority of the mainly Moslem Bosnian troops defending the 
city against a 22-month Serb siege. 
  Silajdzic said that the NATO ultimatum could lead to a 
"balance of power and with a balance of power you will have 
peace." He denied that the Bosnians were outnumbered since he 
said they were fighting not just Bosnian Serb forces but troops 
from Serbia. "They can bring out more troops at any time," 
Silajdzic said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

