<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Remote Control' Expert Seen at Blast Site </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0902193394 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1857 GMT 9 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0902193394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, Feb 9 (TANJUG) -- A man with glasses, 
filmed by the British television station SKY NEWS a day after 
the massacre at the Sarajevo market on Saturday, is an expert 
for remote control, TANJUG learned on Wednesday. 
  Fahrudin Orucevic, an electronics engineer, is the director 
of a military institute. He was recognized by a collegue from 
work who was watching the SKY NEWS program. 
  The footage, broadcast by Belgrade Television on Tuesday, 
shows Orucevic trying to avoid a British reporter who asked him 
what he was doing at the market as he was seen measuring 
something. He then walked away, ran across the street and 
entered a parked vehicle. 
  His former collegue, who asked not to be named in order not 
to jeopardize the security of a number of people from the 
institute, categorically claims that Orucevic could have been in 
charge of a timer -- part of the mine which exploded at the 
Sarajevo market. 
  He claims that, before the war, Orucevic was employed in 
Sarajevo's firm SDU which manufacutred remote control systems, 
and that one year before the start of the war he was in Turkey 
as the manager of the remote control in a mine. 
  As soon as the war broke out, Orucevic was appointed as 
director of the Unis Institute, one of the numerous military 
factories in the former Yugoslav Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina 
which manufacture weapons and ammunition for the Moslem army. 
  Unis was founded and managed by current Moslem Presidency 
Vice-Presidemt Ejup Ganic who is one of the leading ideologists 
of the fundamentalist Islamic followers of Alija Izetbegovic. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

