<F P=100> HUNGARY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jeszenszky Briefs Assembly on Belgrade Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0902183994 Budapest Kossuth Radio Network in Hungarian 
1700 GMT 9 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0902183994 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest Kossuth Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hungarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Today the Hungarian National Assembly's Foreign 
Affairs Committee heard Foreign Minister Geza Jeszenszky's 
report on his visit in Belgrade on 27 January. He confirmed 
once again that Hungary is not going to initiate the lifting of 
the UN embargo. Peter Gyuricza reports from the Committee's 
meeting. 
  [Gyuricza] Events of the following months will prove whether 
changes in Belgrade politics -- which also made possible Foreign 
Minister Jeszenszky's visit -- have indeed taken place. The 
foreign minister said that these changes include the diminishing 
of psychological pressure on ethnic Hungarians in Vojvodina, 
reducing extremist manifestations, easing the tone of the 
Belgrade press, and decreasing the frequency of call-ups. 
  Geza Jeszenszky favorably viewed the fact that negotiations 
are under way between the Democratic Community of Hungarians in 
Vojvodina and the Serbian Government with regard to autonomy and 
its institutions. Geza Jeszenszky said that Hungary will not 
initiate lifting the UN Security Council embargo. At the same 
time, however, as a sovereign state guided by its national 
interests, it may believe that the time has come to hold talks 
about this with its partners and allies, especially since no way 
out can be seen. [passage omitted] Hungary is observing the UN 
Security Council resolution, stressed Geza Jeszenszky. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

