<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karadzic on Ultimatum, Possible Air Strikes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0902203294 Belgrade RTB Television Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1830 GMT 9 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0902203294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade RTB Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] As we have learned, Radovan Karadzic, president of 
the Srpska republic, met with Serbian President Slobodan 
Milosevic in Belgrade today. After the talks, correspondents of 
foreign television stations overwhelmed President Karadzic with 
questions about threats of air strikes. Let us hear how Dr. 
Karadzic answered: 
  [Begin recording] [Unidentified correspondent] Please 
comment on the statement by French Foreign Minister Juppe that 
he will demand an ultimatum for the Serbs, 10 days to withdraw 
20 [words indistinct]. 
  [Karadzic] Minister Juppe should ask [Austrian Foreign] 
Minister Mock about the fate of the Austrian ultimatum in 1914. 
  [Unidentified correspondent, in English fading into 
Serbo-Croatian translation] Will you withdraw your artillery 
from the positions around Sarajevo? 
  [Karadzic, in English fading into Serbo-Croatian 
translation] 
Immediately, as soon as we sign the peace plan. 
  [Unidentified correspondent, in English fading into 
Serbo-Croatian translation] The NATO secretary general today 
said that it was high time to do something in Bosnia. How would 
you comment on this? 
  [Karadzic, in English fading into Serbo-Croatian 
translation] 
Well, had they taken no actions in the former Yugoslavia, it 
would not have disintegrated. I would love it if they would not 
meddle into our affairs at all, because, it is precisely they 
who have caused this war. 
  [Unidentified correspondent, in English fading into 
Serbo-Croatian translation] What will happen if the NATO 
Council issues an ultimatum to the Serbs to withdraw from their 
positions around Sarajevo? 
  [Karadzic, in English fading into Serbo-Croatian 
translation] 
How can we withdraw from Sarajevo? Sarajevo is not a 
surrounded town, but a divided town. We hold half of the town. 
If somebody is asking us to give up our own town, then no, 
never, out of the question. 
  [Unidentified correspondent, in English fading into 
Serbo-Croatian translation] Do you believe in air strikes, Mr. 
Karadzic? 
  [Karadzic, in English fading into Serbo-Croatian 
translation] 
I believe in God. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

