<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karadzic: NATO Flexing `Muscles' Needlessly </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1002201994 Belgrade RTB Television Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1830 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1002201994 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade RTB Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic by </F>
unidentified correspondents in Geneva on 10 February -- 
recorded; Karadzic and correspondents speak in English with 
superimposed Serbo-Croat translation] 
  [Correspondent] Mr. Karadzic, do you plan to withdraw the 
Serbian troops as is stipulated in the agreement on the 
cease-fire brokered yesterday? 
  [Karadzic] The cease-fire was agreed upon a week ago and is 
not connected to NATO threats or the ultimatum. I believe that 
NATO is knocking at an open door and is flexing its muscles 
absolutely needlessly. Our commanders have drawn up some kind 
of agreement on a permanent cease-fire around Sarajevo. I have 
spoken to Mr. Akashi about this issue, and I prepared all this. 
This has nothing to do with NATO. 
  [Correspondent] You will maintain the cease-fire? 
  [Karadzic] Yes. It has been brokered by the representatives 
of the [warring] sides and Mr. Akashi. NATO has nothing to do 
with us. 
  [Correspondent] Neither the Croats, the Muslims, nor the 
cochairmen want a joint commission to investigate the [5 
February] Sarajevo event. Will you go on demanding it? 
  [Karadzic] We have encouraging information that a commission 
will be formed and that a Serbian expert will be part of it. 

</TEXT>

