<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karadzic: Pullback Not Due to Ultimatum </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1202160094 Paris AFP in English 1524 GMT 12 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1202160094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, Feb 12 (AFP) -- Bosnian Serb leader Radovan 
Karadzic confirmed in Geneva Saturday [12 February] that his 
forces would withdraw their heavy artillery from Sarajevo, but 
he also that said Moslem infantry must be controlled. NATO has 
issued an ultimatum for all heavy weapons to be withdrawn from 
Serb-besieged Sarajevo by February 21 or its warplanes will 
destroy the guns. The NATO demand issued last Wednesday does 
not include infantry or light weapons. 
  Karadzic said the Serb agreement to withdraw its heavy 
artillery was not in respect of the NATO ultimatum but according 
to a previous agreement reached with the UN envoy for Yugoslavia 
Yasushi Akashi. "On 5th of February I agreed with Mr. Akashi a 
settlement for long-lasting ceasefire in Sarajevo and this 
agreement envisaged on-site control of heavy weaponry of both 
sides Serbian and Moslem," Karadzic said. 
  "We are not members of NATO. We do not live with NATO. We 
have agreed this ceasefire with Moslems brokered by Mr. Akashi 
and this agreement envisaged control of Moslem infantry," 
Karadzic said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

