<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Talks on Bosnia Peace Continue in Geneva </TI></H3>
<H4>   Karadzic Criticizes Muslims </H4>
<F P=102> LD1202151094 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1431 GMT 12 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1202151094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Geneva, February 12 (TANJUG) -- President of the 
Serb republic Radovan Karadzic said in Geneva on Saturday that 
the Moslem side at the talks on Bosnia-Herzegovina was not 
acting in good faith but was trying to gain time and provoke a 
foreign military intervention. This is the very reason why any 
interference by NATO, which sent an ultimatum to Bosnian Serbs, 
would be completely wrong, Karadzic said ahead of his talks with 
the Bosnian Croat delegation which began this morning. 
  "I have seen on television that the Serb artillery is being 
withdrawn from around Sarajevo and I hope that this is true," 
Croat delegation head Mile Akmadzic said prior to the talks, 
underscoring that "this will indeed be a step towards peace if 
the artillery is removed." 
  No significant progress was made at the talks between the 
warring sides during the previous two days. The essential 
question--the future organization of Bosnia and its territorial 
division--cannot be resolved by the negotiators at this time, 
since Moslems rejected the concept of a union of three 
republics, proposing instead a model of 17 cantons within a 
single state of Bosnia. 
  The Moslem side also refused to discuss a separate agreement 
on the demilitarization of Sarajevo and the placing of this city 
under a two-year U.N. administration, which was proposed by the 
co-chairmen of the Conference on Former Yugoslavia in order to 
arrive at a comprehensive agreement more easily. 
  Lord Owen, one of the two co-chairmen, also warned on 
Saturday that there would be no progress in the talks until the 
expiry of NATO's ultimatum to Bosnian Serbs--that they would be 
bombed unless they withdrew their heavy weapons to 20 km from 
the center of Sarajevo by the midnight of February 20. 
  Lord Owen said that the Moslems would wait to see the 
results 
of this ultimatum, so that it will not be possible to get the 
peace process moving before the expiry of this deadline. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

