<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Talks on Bosnia Peace Continue in Geneva </TI></H3>
<H4>   Karadzic Accepts Proposal on Union </H4>
<F P=102> AU1302195894 Belgrade RTB Television Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1830 GMT 13 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1302195894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade RTB Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Radovan Karadzic, president of the republic </F>
of Srpska, by unidentified correspondent; date and place not 
given -- recorded; in English with superimposed translation into 
Serbo-Croatian] 
  [Text] [Correspondent] Would you please be so kind as to 
comment on Lord Owen's statement to the effect that you have 
agreed to the new proposal on the Bosnian union? According to 
that proposal, the Serbs would not have the right to leave the 
Bosnian union. 
  [Karadzic] No, we have accepted the Bosnian union, but 
according to the Muslim-Serbian declaration, we have the right 
to leave it whenever we wish. We may be within the union or 
outside it. If at any given moment this is easier for reaching 
peace, we are going to accept the union as well. 
  [Correspondent] Do you think that the danger of air strikes 
is greater or smaller as compared to the situation two days ago? 
  [Karadzic] This has never depended on our behavior. This is 
an internal problem of the NATO pact. 

</TEXT>

