<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jastrzebie Coal Company Dispute Reported Ended </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1102141994 Warsaw TVP Television First Program Network in 
Polish 1100 GMT 11 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1102141994 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw TVP Television First Program Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Relayed by Warsaw TV Polonia Network] </F>
  [Text] An agreement was reached early this morning between 
the strike committee and the board of the Jastrzebie Coal 
Company. The Miners Trade Union, however, has withdrawn from 
the signing of the protocol. 
  [Correspondent Adam Sojka] The agreement envisages a 
7.2-percent pay increase for January, compared to December last 
year, and a 10-percent increase for February, as compared to 
January. Earnings will remain at the February level in March. 
Moreover, the union side has pledged that it will only use 
legal means of protest in the future, means that are provided by 
the law on trade unions. 
  At the same time, the board announced that it will request 
the law-enforcement bodies to stop criminal proceedings against 
people involved in the blockade of the board's offices and radio 
broadcasting networks in collieries. Both sides have agreed 
that no pay is due for the period of the strike, and the 
financial compensation for people who did not work will take 
place after making up for lost output. The board of the 
company, however, stipulated that the agreement would come into 
force when it is signed by all the trade unions. Only the 
Miners Trade Union refrained from initialling the agreement. At 
the moment, negotiations are being held concerning this matter. 
Unofficially, we have learned that the strike may be suspended, 
possibly even today. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

