<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Welcomes Pressure in Letter </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1102191794 Zagreb HTV Television in Serbo-Croatian 1830 
GMT 11 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1102191794 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb HTV Television </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mate Granic, Croatian deputy prime minister and 
minister of foreign affairs, has sent a letter to United Nations 
Secretary General Butrus-Ghali, informing him about the 
constructive atmosphere and results achieved in negotiations 
with Bosnia-Herzegovina Prime Minister Haris Silajdzic in Geneva 
on 9 and 10 February. In his letter Minister Granic informs 
Butrus-Ghali about the readiness displayed by both sides to 
intensify negotiations which have been initiated on the 
resolution of remaining contentious issues and future relations 
between the Croatian and the Bosnian Muslim nations. 
  Minister Granic welcomes the consent given by the 
governments 
of the United States, European, and other countries for pressure 
to be stepped up on all the warring sides in Bosnia-Herzegovina, 
in order to reach a final solution on the basis of the European 
Union action plan. Minister Granic also expresses support for 
the NATO readiness to use force to lift the siege of Sarajevo, 
which represents the first step in the implementation of that 
plan. 
  The Croatian minister of foreign affairs also informs the UN 
secretary general about Croatia's readiness to meet the request 
of the UN Security Council to reduce tensions between the 
Croatian and Muslim sides in Bosnia-Herzegovina, in the spirit 
of a cease-fire agreement that the two sides have previously 
signed. 
  The Croatian government will also turn to UNPROFOR [UN 
Protection Force] representatives in order to coordinate the 
verification of moves by the Croatian Government and the 
Croatian Defense Council, which should reduce tension and 
rebuild trust between the Croatian and Muslim sides, 
particularly in central Bosnia and in Mostar. 
  The Croatian Government asks the UN Security Council to 
offer 
guarantees with regard to halting the offensive actions of the 
Army of Bosnia-Herzegovina in these areas, in the spirit of the 
aforementioned Geneva negotiations. 

</TEXT>

