<H3> <TI>   First Round of Talks `Cooperative' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1202125894 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1200 GMT 12 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1202125894 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] This morning's round of Croatian-Yugoslav talks at 
the level of deputy prime ministers has ended. Croatian Deputy 
Prime Minister Mate Granic, his guest, Yugoslav Deputy Prime 
Minister Zeljko Simic, and their associates met, it was 
announced, to review humanitarian issues and the possibilities 
for establishing communications links between the two 
neighboring but still mutually unrecognized countries. 
  After brief talks between the two delegations in their 
entirety, the meeting continued between the delegation heads and 
their closest aides, who discussed political issues. Working 
groups on humanitarian issues and communications links held 
separate meetings at the same time. 
  According to assessments made at the beginning of the talks, 
the purpose of today's meeting is to resolve problems over which 
there is a convergence of views between the two countries; 
however, open questions may arise, and the two sides should at 
least coordinate methods and dynamics for resolving them. 
  Croatian circles have noted that this morning's round of 
talks was held in a cooperative working atmosphere. This 
particularly applies, reporters were told, to the talks 
conducted by the mixed commissions for refugees, expelled, and 
missing persons. 
  Talks between the Yugoslav and Croatian deputy prime 
ministers and their associates will continue this afternoon. 

</TEXT>

