<H3> <TI>   Krajina Minister Comments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1302200294 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1942 GMT 13 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1302200294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Knin, Feb 13 (TANJUG) -- Republic of Serb Krajina 
(R.S.K.) Foreign Minister Slobodan Jarcevic said on Sunday he 
was confident that Yugoslavia's leadership would not do anything 
to Krajina's disadvantage while negotiating with Croatia on the 
normalization of their relations. 
  The delegations of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia and 
Croatia on Saturday had talks in Zagreb on the normalization of 
their relations, based on the declaration signed in Geneva 
mid-January. 
  Jarcevic reiterated that these talks had included a large 
number of issues, ranging from humanitarian to political issues, 
and underscored he held the view that Croatia was responsible 
for the exile of 300,000 Serbs, who did not in any way violate 
the laws of the new Croatian government. For that reason, 
Croatia should be 'put before the bar of justice,' Jarcevic said. 
  On the issue of the re-opening of communications, in 
particular the Zagreb-Belgrade motorway, Jarcevic repeated the 
already familiar conditions set by R.S.K. that had to be 
fulfilled first: peace must be established between R.S.K. and 
Croatia and Croatia must allow R.S.K. to establish foreign trade. 
  R.S.K. was proclaimed in 1991 in predominantly 
Serb-populated 
parts of Croatia in response to its forcible secession from 
former Yugoslavia and its attempt to reduce the constituent 
nation status of Serbs to that of a national minority. 
  R.S.K. has been the U.N. protected area (UNPA) since March 
1992 and, as planned, it will keep this status until a final 
political solution has been found. 
  After the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia and Croatia had 
signed the declaration on the normalization of their relations, 
Yugoslav Foreign Minister Vladislav Jovanovic said that the 
declaration did not prejudge the issue of the R.S.K. final 
status. 

</TEXT>

