<F P=100> SLOVENIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Denies Recall of U.S. Attache </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1002143594 Ljubljana Radio Slovenia Network in Slovene 
1800 GMT 9 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1002143594 </F>
<F P=104>  Ljubljana Radio Slovenia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Slovene </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] In light of some newspapers writing about the 
alleged replacement of U.S. Ambassador Alan Wendt [as heard], 
the Slovene Government, the U.S. Embassy, and the Defense 
Ministry have issued statements: 
  In its statement, the Slovene Government emphasizes that it 
has no knowledge of any replacements and that it favors 
strengthening good relations with Washington in all spheres. 
The hitherto good cooperation is, to a great extent, also a 
result of the work and efforts of the U.S. Embassy in Ljubljana. 
[passage omitted] 
  The claims of the U.S. Embassy were also supported by our 
Defense Ministry. A brief statement says that Lieutenant 
(Leach) has, from 3 November 1993, lead very successfully a 
liaison group within the Army to Army program, which is aimed at 
exchanging experiences in the military sphere. Claims that 
Lieutenant (Leach) has been recalled is insulting to Mr. Leach 
-- who has, in the meantime, become a great friend of our 
country -- and harms diplomatic efforts, the international 
reputation of Slovenia, and cooperation of our ministry with the 
U.S. Defense Ministry, the Defense Ministry statement says. 

</TEXT>

