<F P=100> SLOVENIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jansa Holds News Conference on Current Issues </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1002164494 Ljubljana Radio Slovenia Network in Slovene 
1430 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1002164494 </F>
<F P=104>  Ljubljana Radio Slovenia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Slovene </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] A news conference was held in the government 
press center this morning, at which Defense Minister Janez Jansa 
spoke of the views of the Defense Ministry toward some current 
issues that are part of responsibility of the Defense Ministry. 
Robert Skerjanc reports: 
  [Begin Skerjanc recording] First Minister Jansa touched upon 
the question why Slovenia still has not joined the Partnership 
for Peace. As the main reason, he stated foot-dragging in 
parliament's acceptance of clear-cut decisions about drawing 
closer to NATO. 
  As the second issue, the minister touched upon yesterday's 
decision by NATO [regarding Bosnia-Herzegovina]. He assessed it 
as the first serious measure referring to the war in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. However, he warned here that the entire 
affair can turn into a failed attempt at sorting out the matters 
in this region or into a threat that the Serbs will, in time, 
skillfully water down. He also pointed at the need to protect 
the direct vicinity, because we can also expect some retaliation 
in case of international intervention. [passage omitted] 
  As a penultimate matter, the minister touched upon, as he 
said, the biggest international scandal, that is, articles in 
some papers that claimed that, because of the allegedly too-good 
relations with the Defense Ministry, the head of the U.S. 
liaison group, Lieutenant (Leach), and U.S. Ambassador Wendt had 
to leave Slovenia. He again warned that such writing is harmful 
for the international reputation of Slovenia as well as the 
cooperation of the Slovene Defense Ministry with the U.S. 
Defense Ministry. [passage omitted] [end recording] 

</TEXT>

