<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-030 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  14 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meciar To Seek Dismissal of Kovac, Moravcik </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1102153694 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1400 
GMT 11 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1102153694 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Slovak Prime Minister Vladimir Meciar indicated that 
he would strive for the dismissal of Deputy Prime Minister Roman 
Kovac and Foreign Minister Jozef Moravcik. He did not rule out 
that he would link the voting on the privatization bill to the 
vote of confidence in the government. Kovac and Moravcik, who 
head the alternative platform within the ruling Movement for a 
Democratic Slovakia [HZDS], proposed to form a new government in 
which opposition parties would also participate. However, it 
would be a government without Meciar. The prime minister also 
claimed that, of the 10 HZDS deputies who joined the Alternative 
of Political Realism, not all of them would vote for voicing no 
confidence in his government. 
  Speaking about the Alternative's proposal regarding a broad 
coalition government without political leaders, he remarked that 
the real purpose of this was to remove political leaders from 
the government coalition between the HZDS and the Slovak 
National Party. Meciar said that a broad coalition would not 
last because the parties would be bound together only by 
material interest. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

