<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gvero Demands Guarantees for Withdrawal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1302144994 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1256 GMT 13 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1302144994 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kragujevac, 13 Feb (TANJUG) -- "If we were to accept 
the unreasonable demand that only our artillery be removed -- by 
20 km from our positions on the Sarajevo front line -- that 
would mean that we have abandoned our territory and left the 
Serb population with no protection and at the mercy of 50,000 
poisonously religious fanatics and anti-Serb Muslim fighters," 
General Milan Gvero, deputy chief of the general staff of the 
army of the Srpska republic, said today in the "Hallmark of the 
Times" program on Kragujevac radio. 
  Saying that no one in his right mind could accept this 
either 
in a military or a human sense, Gvero stressed that immediately 
after the withdrawal Muslim forces would take the Serb 
positions. This is why he has demanded a sensible agreement in 
the direction of peace. 
  "We must have guarantees that, if our army withdraws by a 
single kilometer, the Muslim army will do the same and that 
their infantry will not advance by a single inch. If there are 
no such guarantees we are dutybound to remain where we are now, 
because of the bloodshed and the people," Gvero added. In his 
words, there is a false image in the world of Sarajevo as a 
Muslim city. This is a territory which is Serbian in every 
respect, so the term siege is inappropriate and at odds with the 
facts. 
  The demand to tilt the balance of force to the detriment of 
Serb forces is unrealistic and unfulfillable. In Gvero's view, 
this is a criminal attitude to our territory, our people, and 
our army. 
  General Gvero stressed that NATO's ultimatum was a 
consequence of the emotions created by the Sarajevo massacre, 
and it is a fact that the massacre was staged. 
  Asked to comment on President Clinton's statement that one 
should not fear the Bosnian Serbs' air defense, which is 
allegedly totally outdated and in poor repair, Gen. Gvero said: 
"If someone attacks us for no reason whatever we will, just as 
always in the past, find a way to neutralize the attacker. No 
one should speculate as to what weaponry we possess. We have 
enough weapons for effective defense. I believe that reason will 
prevail, but if insanity prevails it will be met with an 
appropriate reaction." 

</TEXT>

