<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Akashi Meets With UN, NATO Commanders </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1302182094 Paris AFP in English 1659 GMT 13 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1302182094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Zagreb, Feb 13 (AFP) -- The UN secretary-general's 
special envoy met with commanders of the UN Protection Force 
(UNPROFOR) and NATO's Southern Command here Sunday [13 February] 
to discuss possible air strikes on Bosnian Serb forces besieging 
Sarajevo. 
  The meeting, which came a week ahead of the Febuary 21 
deadline set by the North Atlantic Treaty Organization for the 
Serbs to pull back their heavy guns, grouped Secretary General 
Butrus Butrus-Ghali's special representative Yasushi Akashi, the 
UNPROFOR commanders for ex-Yugoslavia and Bosnia -- Generals 
Jean Cot and Michael Rose -- and Admiral Jeremy Boorda, 
commander of NATO's Southern Command. 
  Akashi told reporters afterwards that the meeting "was to 
make sure that UN and NATO work in concert with each other. It 
was fruitful. It seems that we think in the same way." 
  The talks, held at UNPROFOR's logistics base at Zagreb 
airport, marked the third time since Tuesday that General Cot 
and Admiral Boorda had met here to discuss possible NATO air 
action against Serb positions around the Bosnian capital. 
  "This meeting is very important to the success of our mutual 
endeavour," said Boorda's spokesman Captain Jim Mitchell. He 
added that the talks aimed to define "whose the responsibilities 
are" on "both sides of this team." 

</TEXT>

