<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs, Government Forces Surrender More Weapons </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1302193894 Paris AFP in English 1925 GMT 13 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1302193894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Helene Despic-Popovic] </F>
  [Excerpts] Sarajevo, Feb 13 (AFP) -- Bosnian Serb and 
government forces surrendered fresh batches of heavy weapons to 
UN troops Sunday as a ceasefire around the city entered its 
fourth day with only minor violations, UN spokesmen said. 
  UN Protection Force [UNPROFOR] spokesman Major Bill Aikman 
told a press conference late Sunday (13 February] that 13 Serb 
and five Bosnian Army weapons had been handed over to UNPROFOR 
during the day after a 24-hour break in the disarmament process. 
  The Serbs handed over two 100 mm cannon, two 155 mm cannon, 
a 
122 mm mortar, six 82 mm mortars and two multiple 
rocket-launchers, Aikman said. 
  The mainly-Moslem Bosnian army for its part dismantled and 
placed under UN control a 75 mm anti-aircraft gun, two others of 
75 and 37 mm, and two 82 mm mortars. [passage omitted] 
  The ceasefire entered its fourth day midday Sunday with only 
a "small number of violations," Aikman said, adding 15 shells 
were fired in the city in the last 24 hours. [passage omitted] 
  Meanwhile in Zagreb Yasushi Akashi, UN Secretary General 
Butrus Butrus-Ghali's special representative in Bosnia, stressed 
the air strike threat applied to all three of Bosnia's warring 
parties. 
  Speaking after meeting Sunday with UN and NATO commanders to 
coordinate possible implementation of air strikes, Akashi said 
that, in the event of bombardments being ordered, NATO would 
carry them out "against whichever party was violating the 
ceasefire." 
  UNPROFOR's Bosnia commander General Sir Michael Rose, who 
attended the meeting, added that many of the truce violations 
registered in Sarajevo had been carried out by Bosnian 
government troops. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

