<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Silajdzic, Assembly President Report on Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1302195594 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1800 GMT 13 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1302195594 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Bosnia-Herzegovina Prime Minister Haris Silajdzic 
and Assembly President Miro Lazovic held a news conference today 
upon their return from Geneva. 
  The Geneva negotiations and the withdrawal of the 
aggressor's 
artillery from around Sarajevo were the main focus. We have 
just received Mladen Bosnjak's report: 
  [Begin recording] [Bosnjak] Mr. Silajdzic, what were the 
results of your talks with [Croatian Foreign Minister Mate] 
Granic? Mr. Lazovic, how was the proposal on the three-way or 
four- way organization of the authorities and territory of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina--made by the Bosnian Croat 
convention--received in Geneva? 
  [Silajdzic] I think we held four meetings with Mr. Granic. 
We agreed, first, that military commanders should meet and try 
to put into effect a total cease-fire. We also agreed that both 
sides completely supported a project entitled All Return Home. 
That means creating conditions for everyone to return home, for 
everyone who has been expelled to be able to go back home. I 
think that we owe such an approach to our era and to this 
civilization. I am pleased that the Croatian delegation 
accepted such an approach. 
  We also agreed that the talks should be intensified and 
should resume. 
  [Lazovic] I can say the proposal by the Bosnian Croat 
convention--which had been accepted by the Bosnia-Herzegovina 
Assembly--was received with real interest in Geneva. 
  That was the first time that Bosnian Croats appeared before 
the international public with a policy completely different from 
that of Zagreb. The delegation of the Bosnian Croat convention 
clearly said at a news conference that they represented 
two-thirds of the Bosnian Croats and that they denied the right 
of legitimacy to Akmadzic and others who are really entitled 
only to represent western Herzegovina. 
  This is a complete novelty in the policy of the Bosnian 
Croats. I am convinced that the official policy of the Republic 
of Croatia will have to take this into consideration in the 
upcoming period. It is interesting that even the representatives 
of the so-called Srpska republic listened to the proposal with a 
certain degree of interest. If the activities of the Bosnian 
Croats achieve satisfactory results in the coming period, 
particularly in the international arena, I believe that a change 
could be brought about that is favorable to the overall 
Bosnia-Herzegovina policy. [end recording] [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

