<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mostar Designated as Capital of Herceg-Bosna </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0902195194 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1837 GMT 9 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0902195194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Zagreb, Feb 9 (TANJUG) -- The parliament of the 
Bosnian Croat Republic of Herceg-Bosna has decided that the 
former Yugoslav republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina should be a union 
of three constituent nations enjoying the same rights. 
  The Bosnian Croats' constitutional rights and right of 
self-determination can be exercised through the Bosnian Croat 
Republic of Herceg-Bosna in a union of three republics of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, provided that the right is observed of the 
other two constituent nations, Bosnian Moslems and Serbs, to 
have their own republics based on the same principles -- says a 
declaration adopted by 400 participants in the parliament 
session of the Bosnian Croat Republic of Herceg-Bosna late on 
Tuesday. 
  According to this document, Mostar, the largest town in the 
Herzegovina region and its administrative centre, in which 
pitched battles are being fought between Bosnian Croat and 
Bosnian Moslem troops, is to be the capital of the Bosnian Croat 
Republic of Herceg-Bosna and 'an indivisible urban entity.' 
  The participants in the parliament session held in Livno, a 
town in western Herzegovina, have supported Franjo Tudjman's 
policy i.e. his 'peace initiative,' in particular the agreement 
on the normalization of relations between Croatia and the 
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia signed within the international 
conference on the former Yugoslavia in Geneva last month. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

