<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lilic Sends Cable to Butrus-Ghali on Ultimatum </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1102194794 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1835 GMT 11 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1102194794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 11 Feb (TANJUG) -- In reaction to the 
latest developments in and around Bosnia-Herzegovina, FRY 
[Federal Republic of Yugoslavia] President Zoran Lilic has sent 
a telegram to UN Secretary General Butrus-Ghali. 
  According to the FRY President's Office, the telegram says 
that the FRY upholds the European Union's proposal on resolving 
the crisis in Bosnia-Herzegovina, as well as the agreement on a 
cease- fire and the demilitarization of Sarajevo signed by the 
Bosnian Serb and Muslim sides. 
  The FRY president stresses that this gives Yugoslavia all 
the 
more reason to be concerned over NATO's perplexing decision to 
search for a solution through ultimatums and military might, and 
adds that such decisions could invoke the continuation of the 
war, while peace can only be achieved through negotiations on an 
equal footing. NATO's decision is an unauthorized assumption of 
the UN Security Council's political competences by this military 
alliance. 
  President Lilic also says that the FRY is firmly convinced 
that the United Nations alone is authorized to reach such 
political decisions, especially concerning the use of force. 
  The FRY president also appeals to the UN secretary general 
to 
take all necessary measures in order that the UN Security 
Council may regain its usurped political rights in resolving the 
crisis in former Bosnia-Herzegovina [as received], which would 
ensure a successful outcome of the Geneva peace process. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

