<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Spokesman: Air Strikes Will Lead to War </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1002144594 Paris AFP in English 1440 GMT 9 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1002144594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, Feb 10 (AFP) -- NATO air strikes against 
Bosnian Serb positions around Sarajevo would lead to war in the 
Balkans and even Europe, a military spokesman for the rump 
Yugoslavia warned Thursday. 
  "It would provoke a big war in the Balkans and even in 
Europe 
and UN peacekeepers would then become enemies of the Serbs," 
Colonel Ljubodrag Stojadinovic said in reponse to NATO's 
ultimatum warning the Serbs to withdraw all of their heavy 
weapons from around Sarajevo by February 21 or face raids by 
NATO warplanes. 
  His warning, carried by the Bosnian Serb news agency SRNA, 
was the first official Serb reaction to the ultimatum, which was 
sparked by the weekend attack on a Sarajevo market that left 68 
people dead and 197 wounded. 
  Stojadinovic said the massacre was nothing but a "bloody and 
fabricated farce" adding that he backed calls by Bosnian Serb 
leader Radovan Karadzic for an investigation into the attack. 
  Karadzic walked out of peace talks in Geneva Thursday, 
saying 
he refused to participate unless the responsibility for the 
mortar attack was determined. 
  The semiofficial Yugoslav news agency TANJUG also criticized 
the NATO ultimatum Thursday saying that it reflected a decision 
made by "mediocre politicians." 
  "A group of mediocre politicians, especially those within 
the 
European Community, are making mistakes that are becoming more 
and more serious, without learning any lessons from previous 
mistakes," the agency, which generally reflects the Serb 
government's opinion, said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

